[[Category:ISO 639]]

In [[linguistics]], [[discourse analysis]], and related fields, an '''interlocutor''' is a person involved in a [[conversation]] or [[dialogue]]. Two or more people speaking to one another are each other's interlocutors.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |year=2003 |title =interlocutor ''noun'' |encyclopedia=Merriam-Webster's Collegiate Dictionary, Eleventh Edition |publisher=Merriam Webster |isbn=0877798095}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://cw.routledge.com/textbooks/meyerhoff/glossary.asp |accessdate=2013-05-12 |title=Routledge Sociolinguistics Glossary |work=Introducing Sociolinguistics, 2nd edition |last=Meyerhoff  |first=Miriam |year=2013 |publisher=Taylor and Francis}}</ref>  The terms ''conversation partner'',<ref>{{cite book|last=Thomas|first=Margaret |title=Fifty Key Thinkers on Language and Linguistics|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nw_OjgTSCkkC&pg=PA280|accessdate=2013-05-12|year=2011|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-0-415-37302-9|page=280}}</ref> ''hearer'',<ref>{{cite book|editor=Buchstaller, Isabelle and Ingrid Van Alphen|title=Quotatives: Cross-linguistic and Cross-disciplinary Perspectives|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hi-0qRYc4BgC&pg=PT315|accessdate=12 May 2013|year=2012|publisher=John Benjamins Publishing|isbn=978-90-272-3905-1|page=285|chapter=Appendix: Glossary of specialist terms for research in quotation}}</ref> or ''addressee''<ref>{{cite book|last=Whitley|first=M. Stanley |title=Spanish-English Contrasts: A Course in Spanish Linguistics|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yyqU_tXek1EC&pg=PA358|accessdate=12 May 2013|year=2002|publisher=Georgetown University Press|isbn=978-0-87840-381-3|page=358}}</ref> are oftentimes used interchangeably with ''interlocutor''.

