{{Infobox language |name=Namibian Black German |nativename=''Küchendeutsch'' |states=[[Namibia]] |speakers= none |familycolor=Pidgin |family=German-based pidgin |iso3=none |glotto=none }}
'''Namibian Black German''', also '''NBG''', ({{lang-de|Küchendeutsch}}, "kitchen German") is a [[pidgin]] language of [[Namibia]] that derives from [[German language|standard German]].<ref>{{cite book |title=Markedness and salience in language contact and second-language acquisition: evidence from a non-canonical contact language |series=Language Sciences |volume=25 |last=Deumert |first=Ama |doi=10.1016/S0388-0001(03)00033-0 |date=2003 |publisher=Elsevier Ltd}}</ref> It is nearly extinct. It was spoken mostly by Namibians who did not learn standard German during the period of [[German South-West Africa|German rule]]. It was never a first language. It is currently spoken as a second language by people over 50 years old,{{when|date=May 2015}} who these days usually also speak German, [[Afrikaans]], or English.{{citation needed|date=May 2015}}
== History == Colonial acquisition of German in Namibia often took place outside of formal education and was primarily self-taught. Like many pidgin languages, Namibian Black German developed through limited access to the standard language and was restricted to the work environment.
Currently several hundred thousand Namibians speak German as a second language, and while [[German language in Namibia#Namibian German as a dialect|Namibian German]] often does not adhere to standard German, it is not pidgin.{{cn|date=September 2016}}
==Prepositions== English and Afrikaans have left an influence on the development of NBG, leading to three primary prepositional patterns:{{citation needed|date=May 2015}} *adding a preposition where Standard German would use the accusative *dropping prepositions which are usually present in Standard German *changing the preposition that is required by the verb
==Examples== Examples of phrases with Standard German equivalents: * ''Lange nicht sehen ''- long no see ("Lange nicht gesehen") * ''Was Banane kosten? ''- How much does the banana cost? ("Was kostet die/eine Banane?") * ''spät Uhr'' - 'late hour', meaning 'it's late' ("es ist spät") * ''Herr fahren Jagd, nicht Haus'' - "Master went hunting and he's not at home" ("Der Herr ist zur Jagd gefahren und ist nicht zu Hause")
